My be this won&#39;t solve your problem but it will help you to diagnose it. Your problem may be caused by multiple causes. Two major ones are:

 1. The Telugu text gets corrupted before it gets passed to iText library;
 2. your computer may not have Telugu true type font installed so iText library doesn&#39;t know what to print in. (or some other problem related to iText library)

So, in order to find out which one try to pass Unicodes sequence representing your Telugu text instead of actual Telugu text. In your example replace the line:

    c1 = new PdfPCell(new Phrase(&quot;పాఠశాల పేరు&quot;, font));
with:

    c1 = new PdfPCell(new Phrase(&quot;\\u0c2a\\u0c3e\\u0c20\\u0c36\\u0c3e\\u0c32\\u0020\\u0c2a\\u0c47\\u0c30\\u0c41&quot;, font));
Just to make it clear The Unicode sequence That represents string `&quot;పాఠశాల పేరు&quot;` is `\u0c2a\u0c3e\u0c20\u0c36\u0c3e\u0c32\u0020\u0c2a\u0c47\u0c30\u0c41` If the problem still persists than it points out that your text was passed correctly and iText library has a problem writing it properly into PDF. When I encountered problem like this I found that I didn&#39;t have needed true type font installed on my computer. However, if passing Unicode sequence solves your problem, it means that your Telugu text got corrupted before it was passed to iText library.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
There are a lot of ways to convert any text into Unicode sequence. I used my own util that does it. If you interested - youcan use Open Source java library MgntUtils written and maintained by me that has a Utility that converts Strings to unicode sequence and vise versa:

    result = &quot;Hello World&quot;;
    result = StringUnicodeEncoderDecoder.encodeStringToUnicodeSequence(result);
    System.out.println(result);
    result = StringUnicodeEncoderDecoder.decodeUnicodeSequenceToString(result);
    System.out.println(result);

The output of this code is:

    \u0048\u0065\u006c\u006c\u006f\u0020\u0057\u006f\u0072\u006c\u0064
    Hello World

The library can be found at [Maven Central][1] or at [Github][2] It comes as maven artifact and with sources and javadoc

Here is javadoc for the class [StringUnicodeEncoderDecoder][3]


  [1]: https://search.maven.org/artifact/com.github.michaelgantman/MgntUtils/1.5.0.2/jar
  [2]: https://github.com/michaelgantman/Mgnt
  [3]: http://michaelgantman.github.io/Mgnt/docs/com/mgnt/utils/StringUnicodeEncoderDecoder.html

